  <discussion>Sarcocornia pacifica appears to be endemic to the Americas, although its precise
        delimitation and distribution are unclear. Well-grown plants can be easily recognized by the
        long terminal spikes, but depauperate plants are difficult to distinguish from S. perennis.
        The name Salicornia virginica has often been applied to this species.</discussion>
  <discussion>Salicornia ambigua Michaux, Fl. Bor.-Amer. 1: 2. 1803, may be the earliest name for
        this species, although it could also be a synonym of Sarcocornia perennis. Until the
        taxonomy of the east-coast plants of the genus has been resolved, the application of
        Michaux’s binomial is uncertain.</discussion>
